agbehind inflation for the second straight year, according to a newsurvey.   The survey of 1,260 businesses found that, after taxes, raiseswill not match the increased prices of goods and services bought byurban wage earners and clerical workers, which rose at an annualizedrate of 5.1 percent through August. The survey was releasedWednesday by the compensation consulting firm Hewitt Associates.</TEXT><DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Automakers will phase out someassembly and component plants during the 1990s as they adjust to ashrinking vehicle market, a Chrysler Corp. executive said.   None of the closings should hit Chrysler next year despite aforecast of a 4 percent to 5 percent slump in new vehicle sales,Robert Lutz, president of Chrysler Motors Corp., said Wednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Major airlines are mulling whether they shouldmatch an American Airlines plan that would raise someadvance-purchase fares by more than 15 percent and doublecancellation penalties.   The increases proposed by American, one of the largest carriers,would take effect Sept. 29. They would follow a recent rise in atype of discount fare popular with business travelers, reflecting aneffort by airlines to partly recoup revenue lost from bargainsoffered this summer to fall vacationers.   Spokesmen for competitors of Dallas-based American said Wednesdaythose airlines were considering matching the increases but hadn'tdecided.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government ordered $630,000 in finesagainst Pan Am, alleging the airline failed to properly screenpassengers and cargo for the Boeing 747 blown up over Scotland lastyear.   The Federal Aviation Administration said nothing in its orderWednesday alleged that the violations contributed to the Dec. 21bombing that killed all 259 people aboard the jumbo jet and 11 onthe ground in Lockerbie.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush has rejected a plea by ColombianPresident Virgilio Barco for a one-year reinstatement of acoffee-export quota system that benefitted Colombian farmers, theWhite House said.   Colombian coffee prices have fallen sharply since the 74-nationInternational Coffee Agreement _ to which both the United States andColombia belonged _ collapsed in July after the United States pulledout in a dispute over prices with coffee-producing nations.</TEXT><DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbachersigned investment and tourism agreements and extended his stay tonegotiate a pact to persuade American companies to do business inthe new Poland.   The proposed accord signed Wednesday would address the concernsof U.S. companies considering investing in the economically andpolitically volatile country, which has the East bloc's onlynon-communist-led government.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock prices hovered in a narrow range Wednesday, as the DowJones average of 30 industrials dropped 3.42 to 2,683.89.   Bond prices suffered a broad setback.   The dollar slumped as investors worried that West Germany mightraise its interest rates.   Coffee futures prices surged and futures prices for energy,precious metals, grains and pork all advanced, while cattle futuresprices declined.</TEXT></DOC>